OBJECTIVE:

•	To interface an Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC 0808/0809) with the 8051 microcontroller.

LEARNING OUTCOMES:

•	Understand the signaling protocol for ADC chips (ALE, START, EOC, and OE).
•	Learn how to select specific analog channels using address lines (ADD A, B, C).
•	Develop an assembly language program to automate the data acquisition process.

EQUIPMENTS REQUIRED: 

8051 trainer kit, ADC 0808/0809 IC, Potentiometer (for analog input).

THEORY:

The ADC 0808 is an 8-bit CMOS device with an 8-channel multiplexer. It uses a successive approximation register (SAR) for conversion. Since the 8051 is a digital device, it requires an ADC to process real-world 
signals like temperature or voltage.

Key control signals used in this code:

•	ALE (Address Latch Enable): Latches the address of the selected channel.
•	START: Begins the conversion process.
•	EOC (End of Conversion): ADC signals the MCU that the data is ready.
•	OE (Output Enable): Enables the output buffers to read the converted digital data.

ALGORITHM
  1.	INITIALIZE PORTS:
      o	 Configure Port 1 as an input port to receive digital data from the ADC.
      o	Clear the ALE (Address Latch Enable) and START pins.
      o	Set EOC (End of Conversion) high as an initial state.
  2.	CHANNEL SELECTION: Select the desired analog input channel by providing the address to pins ADD
      A, B, and C. (In this code, Channel 2 is selected by setting B=1, A=0, C=0).
  3.	LATCH ADDRESS: * Set ALE high.
      o	Apply a short delay.
      o	Set START high to initiate the conversion.
  4.	START CONVERSION: * Apply a short delay.
      o	Clear ALE and START pins to complete the start pulse.
  5.	WAIT FOR EOC: * Monitor the EOC pin.
      o	Wait until EOC goes low (signaling conversion has started).
      o	Wait until EOC goes high again (signaling conversion is complete).
  6.	READ DATA:
      o	Set OE (Output Enable) high to enable the ADC’s output buffers.
      o	Apply a short delay.
      o	Read the 8-bit digital data from Port 1 into the Accumulator.
  7.	DISPLAY DATA: Move the data from the Accumulator to Port 3 for visual output.
  8.	LOOP: Jump back to the BACK label to repeat the process for continuous monitoring.
  9.	END: End of program.

CODE:

ORG 0000H						; Starting address
		MOV P1,#0FFH			; Makes port 1 input port
		SETB P2.7				; Makes EOC pin high
		CLR P2.4				; Clears ALE pin
		CLR P2.6				; Clears Start pin
BACK:	CLR P2.5				; Clears OE pin
		CLR P2.2				; Clears ADD C
		SETB P2.1				; Sets ADD B
		CLR P2.0				; Clears ADD A (this selects the second address line)
		ACALL DELAY
		SETB P2.4				; Sets ALE high
		ACALL DELAY
		SETB P2.6				; sends a command to start conversion
		ACALL DELAY
		CLR P2.4				; makes ALE low
		CLR P2.6				; makes Start pin low
HERE: 	JB P2.7,HERE			; waits for low pulse at EOC
HERE1: 	JNB P2.7,HERE1			; waits for high pulse to finish
		SETB P2.5				; enables OE pin to extract data from ADC
		ACALL DELAY
		MOV A,P1				; moves acquired data to accumulator
		MOV P3,A
		SJMP BACK				; repeatedly gets data from ADC
DELAY: 	MOV R3,#50
HERE2: 	MOV R4,#255
HERE3: 	DJNZ R4,HERE3
		DJNZ R3,HERE2
		RET
		END

PROCEDURE

•	Step 1: Power ON the 8051 Trainer Kit.
•	Step 2: Enter the program by selecting the A (Address) option and specifying the starting address 4100.
•	Step 3: Enter the input using SP (Store Program) starting from the addresses 4600.
•	Step 4: Execute the program using the GO command followed by the program’s starting address.
•	Step 5: Verify the output using SP (Store Program) starting from the addresses 4701.

EXPECTED OUTPUT:

Input: 1.25 V
Output: 3FH

INFERENCE:

The program successfully demonstrates the handshaking process between the 8051 and ADC 0808. By 
manipulating the control pins in the correct sequence, we can reliably convert and read analog 
signals for further processing.
